LOCALITY: Lake Chabot Regional Park --West Shore Trail (Chabot Park, San Leandro Access)
TRIP COMMENTS: Chabot Park in San Leandro has finally re-opened after a nearly two-year closure for dam upgrades and this access point to the dam via West Shore Trail is now available.  Sunny and warm.  The Pine Knoll near the dam overlook has been severely culled with only a few pine snags remaining and about a dozen Ponderosa Pines left in place.  New fencing and a wider newly asphalted trail have been installed.  Pine mulch and grassy fields have replaced much of the brushy underbrush around the Pine Knoll.

SPECIES COMMENTS: From parking lot, I heard weak raptor-type call, unlike Red-tailed Hawk, and observed two Bald Eagles (BAEA) above ridge to the west. One BAEA was an adult (BAEA-1), the other did not have clean white in the tail, with some mottling on the belly (assumed sub-adult) (BAEA-2). As they flew directly over the parking lot, with BAEA-1 pursuing BAEA-2, the latter turned upside-down and raised his/her talons toward BAEA-1. Both birds continued this close interacting and weak calling as they flew over and behind Gudde Ridge to the northeast. This was my first experience hearing BAEAs calling in the wild away from a nest.

LOCALITY: Sacramento National Wildlife Refuge, Willows US-CA (39.4328,-122.1881)
TRIP COMMENTS: A great day at the Sacramento NWR! At the tail end of our 2-mile walk, I spotted a bald eagle soaring. It was surrounded by a turkey vulture, a Red-tailed hawk, and a smaller bird of prey. The eagle alighted in a tree and had a mallard! We watched the feathers of the duck fall to the ground like light and colorful snow. We could hear the sounds of the mallard being pulled apart! My 11 year old spotted another bald eagle in a tree next to the one with the duck. We took the 6-mile auto tour and about a quarter-mile, after rest stop 2 we saw an immature bald eagle in a tree to the right of us. First time seeing an immature. My biggest wish was to see a Peregrine Falcon but unfortunately, it wasnâ€™t to be. There were sightings on the 28th and 29th but not today. I wish I was better at identifying birds because the list would have been longer.

TRIP COMMENTS: This was the Redwood Region Audubon Society monthly field trip to Humboldt Bay National Wildlife Refuge. A little rain and wind eventually gave way to stillness and glorious, balmy sun! We were rewarded for our resolve. Gone were the Ruby-crowned Kinglets, and in their place we enjoyed many breeding-plumaged Myrtle and Audubon's Yellow-rumped Warblers. Thanks for coming!----PS: I didn't keep careful eBird tallies, so if there are missing species, or my numbers are way off, please let me know and I'll send out an amended list to everyone.----PPS: A few species on the list were seen or heard along the frontage road or in the parking lot after the trip ended.

observed from car without binoculars.  First noticed flying low ahead of me, harassed by 3 corvids which were approximately a factor of 2 smaller in linear dimensions.  (At least one of these was a raven, seen well after it landed on a nearby tree.)  The eagle was flapping wings much more slowly than the corvids, and more slowly and evenly than a RTHA.  It was difficult to see color features on the eagle due to the lighting conditions (overcast skies), but it did make one nearby pass after I pulled into a side street, and it had a white head.  I failed to notice the tail color.  I tried to chase it down by driving, but soon lost it below trees to my northwest.  I drove to the east edge of the Arroyo/Hahamongna basin with broad view to the west, but didn't see the eagle.

SPECIES COMMENTS: My wife and I came up here yesterday on our 30th wedding anniversary, to see if we could spot any signs of the Bald Eagle pair that recently lost  both their nest and their baby that fell with it. To our great surprise, relief and joy, my wife spotted what we think was the male perched in the middle of the tree where their nest once was. The tree to the left looks like it has the beginnings of a new nest at the very top of it. So it looks like this pair are taking up residence again. What a great anniversary present to see that they're still there and that the signs are looking good that they plan on staying.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Pretty shocked by this sighting. Bird was just passing through: circling in thermals above lake before gliding off to the south and out of sight. My pen ran out of ink while taking sketch details so they are much sketchier than normal, but I thought this was a sighting worth documenting one way or another. ----This was a first fall bird. Large dark bird of pray with prominent contrasting white patches on tail and underwing coverts. Primaries and secondaries dark with prominent "fingers".  Head, chest, and belly cool dark brown without warm tones. Underwings (primaries/secondaries) dark but with some white mottling. In particular white mottling at junction of primaries and secondaries, but nothing like young Golden might show. Tail mostly dirty white with a dark terminal band. Tail vaguely pointed or diamond shaped. Bill and head relatively large, but the silhouette didn't scream "bald eagle" the way an adult bird's does: I believe this is because the wings are broader in juvenile birds such as this one. This was a little unsettling in the field because the bird didn't have the "t shape" that an adult bald eagle shows with the wide wings and relatively long tail. This makes the head look a bit shorter than an adult birds relative to the rest of the bird.

With the help of 3 passers-by I found the eagle in its 'usual' large eucalyptus; its former favorite perching branch in the tree in previous years is apparently gone and initially the eagle was obscured from my view.  The first passer-by said that, yes, the eagle had been seen recently. The second said people were watching it from E. Strawberry Drive just minutes earlier. LOCALITY: Merced NWR (Please use a more specific hotspot where possible.)
TRIP COMMENTS: I used both observation decks; the auto route; plus all three walking trails and the photography blind. I detected 50x species (34x Non-pass. + 16x Pass.). Of these, 47x were visual; two were voice-only (Marsh Wren and GHO); one used voice to confirm a weak visual (Red-necked Pheasant). I recorded sixteen species from the first observation deck, including Sandhill Cranes. On Christmas Day I saw very few S. Cranes until the sunset fly-in. Today, S. Crane was the first bird on my list. Their gurgling call dominated the soundscape from the moment I arrived. During the afternoon, I saw large flocks on the ground and in the air â€“ many hundreds, perhaps more than a thousand. I assigned a reddish-looking finch as House Finch even though it was somewhat ambiguous. I saw a few Tree Swallows. I added four more species on the Kestrel trail, including one Spotted Towhee. (This surprised me; I have never seen Sp. Towhee here before.) I walked the Meadowlark trail next. As on Christmas Day, only one section along this trail was fully flooded: the NW corner. This corner was densely populated by Rossâ€™s & Snow Geese. Thousands, perhaps tens of thousands, were packed together, wings almost touching. I waited close to half an hour, hoping the entire flock would take flight, but most held their ground. Even though Rossâ€™s & Snow dominated the flooded area, many other species were present, including: Coot, Black-necked Stilt, White-fronted Goose, N. Shoveler, Green-winged & Cinnamon Teal, Gadwall, Great Egret. I stopped at the bush where I enjoyed magical views of Bushtits on Christmas Day; I did not see any Bushtits today, here or anywhere else. N. Mockingbird was also strangely missing today. I had good luck on the Auto route. As I was driving the southbound leg, I saw a Bald Eagle flying far to my left (east). Even though it must have been a mile away, I could clearly see that it was an adult Bald Eagle. This is the first time that I can recall seeing an eagle here. (1x Bald Eagle was recorded during the CBC.) Also on the southbond leg, I saw one American Avocet â€“ my first of the season, here or anywhere else. (2x Avocets were recorded on the CBC.) I managed to identify two Lincolnâ€™s Sparrows â€“ a fairly common bird that I only learned recently. (52x of these were logged during the CBC). On the eastbound leg I flushed a bird that I saw out of  the corner of my eye for a fraction of a second before it landed and hid. I guessed it was a Pheasant, but based on sight alone I would not have counted it toward my day list total. This is a case where voice made the difference. When I flushed the bird, I heard a flight call that was unfamiliar to me. I wrote down the following in my notepad: â€œNasal caw-caw-caw-caw- repeated ~10x.â€ When I got home, I checked the Cornell website and confirmed that the Red-necked Pheasant makes this sound when flushed. (3x Rednecked Pâ€™s were seen on the CBC.) Before driving the Auto route, I had four ducks on my list: N. Shoveler; Gadwall; Green-winged Teal; Cinnamon Teal.--On the Auto route I added five more, making this a glorious Nine Duck Day:--N. Pintail; Mallard; Bufflehead; American Wigeon; Ruddy Duck. On January 3, twelve duck species were recorded within the CBC circle (not all within Merced NWR), â€“ the nine I saw today, plus the following: Wood Duck, Ring-necked Duck, Canvasback.--On Christmas Day the single parking space for the Photography Blind was occupied, so I had to skip it. Today the space was open so I took the short walk out to the blind. I counted ~20x American White Pelicans on the ground at their favorite spot. While I was walking out to the blind, I saw and photographed a distinctive bird that I didnâ€™t recognize. It was #43 on my day list. In my notes I wrote: â€œNEW?â€ â€“ but after I got home I discovered that my â€œNEWâ€ bird was just a female Red-winged Blackbird. The male and female RWB look very different. I was embarrassed that I wasnâ€™t able to recognize the female of a species that I  see all the time. With RWBâ€™s, as with ducks, I look for the distinctive field marks of the male and manage to ignore the less  distinctive females â€“ they donâ€™t even enter my consciousness. (I suppose this is how most â€œunintentionalâ€ prejudice works: the prejudice exerts itself through subconscious filtering, as opposed to conscious discrimination.) Only today did I break free. I now realize how beautiful and distinctive the female RWB is!--I walked the Bittern trail about an hour before sunset and got to witness the following amusing scene. Large flocks of â€œblackâ€  birds were active at this hour. Most likely I was seeing a mix of RWBâ€™s, Brewerâ€™s, and Starlings, but the only â€œblackâ€ bird that I was able to confirm and include in my day list was the RWB (thanks to its epaulettes). As I neared the turnaround point of the Bittern trail, I noticed a few dozen Sandhill Cranes on the ground, minding their own business. Then a flock containing hundreds of RWBâ€™s took to the air and swarmed the airspace over the cranes. I couldnâ€™t tell if the RWBâ€™s were intentionally harassing the cranes, or merely ignoring their presence. The cranes certainly noticed the RWBâ€™s. I distinctly saw cranes â€œduck their headsâ€ as RWBâ€™s flew past, just as I duck my head reflexively when a bird flies too close for comfort. After several  repetitions of this comical sequence of events, the cranes nonchalantly took to the air and flew to a quieter spot.--Between the Bittern trail and the second observation deck I saw one individual each of four more species: White-faced Ibis; N. Flicker; Ruby-crowned Kinglet; Loggerhead Shrike. I also heard GHOâ€™s calling in the distance. These five birds raised my total to exactly 50x. (I thought I had 51x until I realized my error re:--female RWB.)--Birds that I hoped to see today but didnâ€™t: Black-crowned Night Heron; Common--Yellowthroat; Sora; American Bittern.

SPECIES COMMENTS: As soon as I arrived, I could see a Bald Eagle perched in a eucalyptus tree on the far west shore.  I decided to pay the eagle a visit.  I followed my usual route until I got to the NW corner of the lake.  Then I walked south â€“ along the west shore.  When I got to the eucalyptus trees, tha Bald Eagle was waiting for me.  I was facing the sun as I approached the eagle, so my first pictures were poor.  Fortunately, the eagle remained on its perch as I passed under the tree.  With the sun at my back, I got nice pictures.  I sat down on the sand and ate my lunch, watching the eagle the whole time.  The eagle was facing the lake.  Occasionally it turned its head toward me and made direct eye contact.  I never felt threatened.

I went to the burn pile and toward the creek.   It was cold and shady so I worked the trail along the edge of the open area to the visitor's center.  From there I went up on the road and to the center of the bridge to look for Dippers.  I walked back to the cemetery and then along Kentucky Creek.
SPECIES COMMENTS: This Bald Eagle flew so close past me, I could hear the air in his wings.  Gorgeous early morning view.

TRIP COMMENTS: Lyann Comrack and Cheryl Cobbs met me at my home at 5 a.m. for the drive to Starbucks at Higgins Corner where we met up with most of the other teams.  I had set up with Brad Rist for the gate to the Water Treatment Plant to open at 7 a.m. so we could do our usual route there.  Almost immediately, we found a distinctive "minima" Cackling Goose and maybe two other individuals of a larger subspecies.  See digiscope photos.  By the time we finished our usual loop here, we had tallied 57 species including a surprise Brown Creeper.----We always go from here to Lake of the Pines and stop at every parking lot around the entire lake.  Unfortunately, the friend who usually arranges with the entrance gate to let us in, forgot to do so. We lost 24 valuable minutes until I finally found someone who would do it for us.  We were very happy to find the Bald Eagle on its usual set of pines.  Later that individual or a second one was seen at another location from which we could not see the original pines...hence to be safe, we only reported one individual here.  Horner's group reported one from the nest area while we were at the WTP so I reported two for Area 7.  Each year it seems we have fewer American Coots on the lake and that goes for other species too. I wonder what chemicals are being added to the lake to prevent growth of what American Coots prefer to eat.----We tried my usual area for Rufous-crowned Sparrow with no success, but as Langham luck would have it, a couple drove up to us a bit further down the road and gave us permission to enter an area I had not birded before.  We got the Rufous-crowned Sparrow here and a bonus Steller's Jay.  We were unsuccessful with Phainopepla and California Thrasher.  There are plenty of trees with mistletoe so do not know why that species has declined over the years.  Our only spot for California Thrasher has failed since all the understory was removed from where we always used to see one.  ----We met the three other sub-teams at the Deli at Higgins Corner at 1:10 to collect tally sheets from them since two were leaving and another was only going to quickly recheck an area they visited early in the morning. My sub-team then spent another hour checking areas that had not been visited by the other sub-teams, but departed at 3 p.m. since one of my team members had a party to attend and the other had a weekend guest waiting for her to return.----I missed not being able to stay for the count-down since that is when I get lots of help putting all our data together.
Auburn CBC Area 7 - Thomas, Horner

SPECIES COMMENTS: My original estimate was 3 birds, but I now believe that there to have been 4. I first sighted an adult+immature circling over the Canary Island pine "grove", with the immature heading northwest over the mountain ridge. Later, I saw 2 immatures soaring in the rough direction that the first immature, earlier, had headed. I suspected that one of the 2 immatures was the same as the one I saw near the adult, however these 2 birds both had wearing in the wings which the first did not. The adult was quite vocal as I walked through and I have a suspicion that it was defending a nest, or territory.----The photos show the adult and first immature individually, followed by a photo of the adult+immature in the same shot, followed by a photo of two immatures. The final photo is the second immature, out of the two immature "pair", which I first suspected was the same as the original immature bird.

TRIP COMMENTS: Looked at Warner Basin from a few different vantage points, and then drove over to Richfield Road to look at Conrock Basin and Huckleberry Pond.  Weather:  Periods of rain interrupted the time birding here, with the rain quite substantial at times. After 15 or 20 minutes of rain, it would stop and then even for short periods of time there'd be blue sky and periods of sunshine.  Only for it to quickly cloud over again and resume raining.  So a percentage of the birding was from the car.  It was breezy (5-10 mph, west winds, with some gusts almost  to 15mph towards the end). Temps were estimated to be low to mid-60s (deg. F).  The duration (1 hr., 30 min.) reflects the total birding time; the actual time here was more like 2 hrs., 30 minutes.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Two distant adults, perched on separate power poles, one on the east and another on the south sides of Warner Basin.  I saw that these were present shortly after I drove up and started scanning the area, during a break in the rain.  A few minutes after catching sight of them, one left its perch and flew off out of sight to the west, apparently following the SAR bed.  The other remained on a pole possibly over along Richfield. After a bit I drove over to the east side (Richfield) to see if I could get a little closer, but found it had flown off.

TRIP COMMENTS: Covering the Irvine Lake area and vicinity for the Sea & Sage Audubon's Northeastern Christmas Bird Count, with area leader Nancy Kenyon. Weather: Mostly sunny all day, with only minimal cloud cover. 46 degrees (F) at about 7am, with a high about 69. Gentle breezes in morning (1-2 mph), with moderate SW winds (5-10 mph) in mid-afternoon--at least on the exposed promontory (overlook of the lake on south side). ----Conditions:  Water levels extremely low in the Irvine Lake--likely the lowest I've ever seen the water levels here.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Two adult Bald Eagles. In early morning we saw one adult perched in the usual --pines on the slope north of the lake. At around 8:30 when we were up on the high promontory that overlooks the central southern portion of Irvine Lake, I suddenly noticed--coming right over us--the two adult Bald Eagles being harassed by a raven. They were only about 75 to 100 feet over our heads. Went over so quick only had seconds to get off a bad photo before they were basically then just flying straight away.  Both eagles were then seen sitting in a mostly dead "coast live oak" tree on the slope above the western side of the lake. Later in afternoon only one eagle was still in that oak while the other adult was back in their favorite pines along the slope above the northeastern shoreline of lake.
Flying high overhead, being harassed by two CORA. Looked to be much larger than the CORA. At one point, the BAEA flipped over and appeared to slash his talons toward a CORA.

Retracing the route we covered in the morning on A24, Specifically the Dyson Lane section centered on Roberti Ranch. I am only adding new birds to the earlier list and not recounting already seen birds. Observations were made from car and roadside at various pullouts. Highlights include a PRFA stealing a vole just caught by an adult female NOHA, already being harassed by an adult male NOHA, and a distant view of six sub-adult BAEA with one screaming adult Bald, squabbling over something unseen on the ground, lots of perch trading, wing-raised walking and general mayhem. Beth Hamel was able to photograph some of the RLHA which displayed unique and varied plumage variation; no two were the same. Juvenile Rough-legged Hawk individual identified by shadowy gray smudged distal remiges and retrices.
SPECIES COMMENTS: One adult, full white head and tail, with six sub-adult feeding and fighting over some unseen carrion.

I was sitting at the intersection of Thompson/Winchester Roads in my vehicle, waiting for the light to turn.  I looked up and noticed this Bald Eagle soaring just west of the intersection.  I managed to snap a photo before the light changed, but by then it was flying away, towards the direction of Lake Skinner.  It appears to have some prey in it's talons.  This area is roughly 4 air miles from Lake Skinner, where these birds are becoming more increasingly common year round.

Presumed third year bird observed on the shoreline of ponded water at the bottom of a huge gravel pit. The eagle appeared to be eating an American Coot, as dark feathers could be seen flying. The very large bill was Â½ yellow (yellow on base), and the head was mottled dark with perhaps 30% white feathers. The tail was mottled blackish and white, with at least 4 feathers appearing totally white or nearly so. It flushed when it detected me high above on a bluff overlooking the pit, and proceeded to soar above the pit for about 15 minutes, after which it flew eastward, toward Cabazon.

LOCALITY: Lake Elsinore--south levee and back basin
TRIP COMMENTS: Elsinore CBC.  Observers were Roger McFarland and Julie Szabo.  Weather was clear with no wind, 30 to 55 degrees.  Small puddles still had ice at mid morning.   Saw one Fairy Shrimp in one puddle.   4 Jackrabbits, 2 Desert Cottontails, 1 Ground Squirrel.   Drove out on the levee from the Storm Baseball Stadium to Rome Hill, and returned via the back basin roads to observe on Cereal, Lucerne and Malaga.  Lots of construction at or near the Summerly Homes, large holes were dug to borrow dirt.  A large fish die off had occured at the lake starting on Thursday, 12/27, and continue through today.  Some work crews were cleaning up fish at the north end of the lake and at Elm Grove Beach.   A 10 foot swath of dead fish (mostly carp, but a few catfish and minnow shad) were at the south west shoreline, south of Perret Park.   Birds were feasting on the dead and dying fish.   The back basin gate was closed and locked, no access, but the ponds there are completely dry.    Total miles (back track to stadium 10.1 miles)
SPECIES COMMENTS: First year bird, seen flying just west of the T-peninsula, then flew to Perret Park, and appeared to perch in a large Eucalyptus Tree.

TRIP COMMENTS: Julie and I took a quick look for Gulls and Eagles for CBC follow up
SPECIES COMMENTS: Eagles using Perret Park and Lakepoint park as resting spots.   One first year bird flew off as we arrived at part, being pursued by an American Crow.   The second (an apparent third year bird), perched for a time in a pine tree.  It then flew towards the lake, caught a fish, and Julie watched in her scope as it them flew all the way west to Perret Park carrying the fish.  It was being pursued by two gulls.

LOCALITY: Lake Elsinore--south levee and back basin
TRIP COMMENTS: Julie Szabo and Greg Cross.  We did a thorough search at all gull flocks for the Lesser Black-backed Gull without success.   The shoreline is still littered with dead fish. The grebes, gulls, pelicans, cormorants, eagles and vultures were taking advantage of the plentiful food.  Clear, 30 - 55 degrees.   A light breeze.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Have photos of two of the first year birds.  White axillaries seen on one while it flew towards Perret Park.   Greg saw 3 of the eagles today,  I only saw two of them.

Jim Thomas arrived at 7:30 a.m. on this 48F clear sky morning with no breeze.  We did not have anything special in the yard or the Pit overlook, but did pick up 2 FOS Northern Shovelers on the Pond and Jim spotted a male American Kestrel on the other side of the river.  At the Rock Diagonal overlook, Jim Pompy called to say he had an adult Bald Eagle, the Peregrine Falcon and a Cooper's Hawk at the Mayhew Drain overlook. At the Gristmill Gravel Bar overlook, I picked out a very distant Merlin, the same dark bird we had last week.  I also heard my FOS American Pipit here and later we would see and hear two near the tip of the long gravel bar.  ----As we left Killdeer Island, I was lucky to look in the right place in an oak to see a male Black-throated Warbler. It never called or responded to tape and eventually presented itself for Jim to see it. Halfway down the trail by the Equipment Pad, I saw the perched adult Bald Eagle (FOS) mentioned earlier by Jim Pompy, but the Peregrine and Cooper's Hawk were gone.  I took a distant digiscope photo from that distant location and we never got a closer view.  ----At the Y overlook, I heard my FOS Purple Finch and saw one of the two as they flew upstream. Down past Mayhew Drain overlook I heard two more but only Jim got to see them in the thick willows. At Mayhew Drain overlook, we had FOUR Greater Yellowlegs together and Jim got great digiscope photos.  Our walk back was uneventful except for adding a Herring Gull at Killdeer Island overlook.----We did get to see six river otters and one coyote.  Great morning!!!
SPECIES COMMENTS: We both got distant digiscope photos but I am only showing one of mine

TRIP COMMENTS: Sunny, calm, 64-70 degrees. Bird numbers for many species were very, very low for this time of year. The river was almost devoid of birdlife despite no human activity there. The massive burn on the west end shows almost no sign of recovery yet because of the fall drought. Highlights were fly-over Bald Eagle and Snow Geese, including one blue morph.

TRIP COMMENTS: Jim Pompy and Jim Thomas met me at my home at 6:45 a.m. on this 49F, completely overcast day with no breeze and we drove to the Nimbus Fish Hatchery parking lot where we met up with Sonia Santa Anna.  In less that 10 minutes we were looking at the male White-winged Scoter. It was too far and moving too fast for clear photos, but Jim Thomas got a few to confirm the ID. They were helping me scout for the upcoming December 30, Folsom CBC where I am taking over Ed Harper's area since he is in Montana.  We walked down river about 80 yards past the last hatchery pond for young salmon.----Highlights besides the White-winged Scoter were Peregrine Falcon, Bald Eagle, Mew Gull, Thayer's race of Iceland Gull, and Glaucous-winged Gull.  48 species in 1.5 hours is quite nice.--1

TRIP COMMENTS: 57 F. This is the closet location to where I saw the bulk of the birds. I was shocked to see several hundred gulls circling in kettles overhead. At one point about 50 ravens joined one of the kettles. There is a man made water impoundment at this location. I have never seen so many gulls at the water. The dump is nearby and often hosts a lot of gulls, but usually not this many. The fields adjacent to the water impoundment have recently been disked, attracting many raptors. I spent a lot of time counting and looking at gulls, either circling in the air, or sitting at the edge of the water impoundment. I also spent a lot of time counting "blackbirds" most of which turned out to be starlings!

TRIP COMMENTS: 69 F, 85% thin cloud cover, no wind.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Both birds were standing in or on the nest. The male was there when I arrived, sitting on the edge of the nest. The female flew in and entered the nest. I could not be certain if she was rearranging material inside of the nest, or if she might have been moving an egg in the nest. She may have laid one egg, but I cannot be certain. Checking later, she appeared to be sitting on an egg in the nest with the male still standing guard on the edge of the nest. This is the pair known as "Bob & Bernadette." They were first discovered nesting at this site in 2004. I have been monitoring the nest since that year. The nest is particularly large this year.

TRIP COMMENTS: 35 early a.m. with heavy frost, warming to 54 F; 0% cloud cover on arrival, changing to 70% thin cloud cover later; no wind. This was a thorough coverage on foot, with permission, of the floor of the reservoir which is mostly covered with weedy vegetation at this time. A small, shallow body of water remains at the north end of the reservoir. I used a spotting scope and did not flush any birds. I saw one coyote on the western hillside l near the new vineyard. This type of count produces the best report of which species are present around the reservoir.
SPECIES COMMENTS: First observed atop the small oak on the east side of the reservoir, later moved to the west side atop an oak tree.

TRIP COMMENTS: 52 F, 95% cloud cover, < 3mph. One gang banger vehicle was present, a tan Ford pickup with 1 male, and 2 female occupants.
SPECIES COMMENTS: PRIVATE PROPERTY. DO NOT TRESPASS. MONITORED DAILY AND REMOTELY. Although both adults were present, I did not see any chicks in the nest. Either they are too small (which doesn't fit the timeline), and their heads are not showing yet, or they have perished. I do not know yet. Needs more study. This is the pair, Bob and Bernadette. This nesting site has been in use since 2004. One nest crashed to the ground during Dec. 2014-Jan. 2015. They picked up the nesting material from the ground and rebuilt the nest by the end of Jan. - early Feb. 2015. Due to this late start, they only fledged one eaglet that season. In all other years, they have fledged two eaglets, except for one year, when the male was shot and killed on this road. PLEASE DO NOT POINT CAMERAS AT THIS PAIR, IF OTHER PEOPLE ARE AROUND.

TRIP COMMENTS: Golden Gate Audubon Society walk led by Bonnie Brown and Pauline Yeckley.  We had 15 friends join in and two of those were 9 year old girls.  It was a glorious, sunny, windless Winter morning in SF,  Cool at the start, 49 degrees and slowly warmed up to the mid 60's.  We started at South Lake and then walked counter clockwise to Middle Lake, JFK drive (to check the Great Horned Owl nest - nobody was home today), North Lake, to the Gardeners shed and then back to the cars.  Highlights were:  Allens Hummingbirds!  We saw their swooping behaviour, vertical descents and had a really nice close up look at one in the sunshine at the water source at the south end of North Lake.  Lots of Yellow Rumped Warblers, mostly heard but we did see several as well.  We looked for the Belted Kingfisher at South Lake when we started but didn't see her.  On our way back to South Lake, we did get some great looks at it.  Very active and fun to watch.  The surprise of the morning occured after most people left.  Saw something flying south to north heading towards South Lake and it turned out to be a mature Bald Eagle!  About 6 of us confirmed the sighting.  5 minutes later we saw it again in the northwest direction, soaring.  Wow!  Lovely morning with another great group.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Distinctive white head and tail flying south to north over South Lake at about 1120AM.  Wow.  We then saw it about 5 minutes later a bit more northwest, soaring.  About six of us saw the bird and all agreed it was a mature bald eagle.

TRIP COMMENTS: Bald Eagle Report Site in and around the intersection of Copperopolis Rd. and South Waverly Rd. The 'Birds of Winter' field study, led by Ed Harper, posted an intriguing e-bird report for their field trip Saturday. They saw a bonanza of raptors incl. Golden Eagles, Bald Eagles, Ferruginous Hawks, Prairie Falcons and many more. I visited this area on January 29th. No Goldens but I saw SIX Bald Eagles and five were adults. One was close enough to the road for some photos.
SPECIES COMMENTS: All of the eagles were spaced at odd intervals across a series of far ridges which could be viewed from one spot on Copperopolis Rd. about 1,000 feet from S. Waverly Rd, itself a small hill. As reported by the Harper team there was at least one cow carcass (picked clean) and others were reported I did not see. My photos show some scenes of what I have described here, with captions.

Circling over flooded field filled with ducks, finally landing at muddy edge and began to feed upon unseen (dead) bird.  Once finished, it flew off lazily to the south.  Very large raptor with white head/tail, dark body, harassed by NOHA.

Foggy to clear, calm to 8-12 mph NW wind, 50-68*F; Tom Edell and Roger Zachary. We parked in the main paved lot by the bathrooms and walked the trail down to the beach and then along the beach to the western end of the cove where we took the path up the slope and then along the bluff top to the point. At the point, we headed north along the bluff top (primarily on the trail through the cypress row, to the end of the cypress and then a little farther along the silver lupine dominated treeless area before turning around and retracing our path back to the parking lot. Once there, we walked to the south east corner of the parking lot to check the red flowering gum (Corymbia ficifolia) for hummingbirds and then walked back to the car.  According to the eBird Android phone app, the total distance covered was 3.9 miles. Using Google Earth the one-way distance covered was about 1.83 miles.

SPECIES COMMENTS: As I was driving northbound I could see a Very large raptor flying steady southbound with a flat flight dihedral coming towards me. It was quite low and right along the shore/beach and flapped slowly several times between glides. As it approached I easily recognized the full adult Bald Eagle flying just above eye level. Full white head with large yellow bill, full white tail and massive chocolate brown body and wings. Great day of coastal birding.

LOCALITY: Lake Cachuma, marsh E Arrowhead Isl.
TRIP COMMENTS: I'm here to find habitat that might harbor shorebirds. There is very little such habitat on the lake accessible from the County Park. To summarize, I also found no visible shorebird habitat here. Large rattler at first stop. The drought allowed so much vegetation to occupy flats and channels; if habitat is present, its not visible from shore. --The chalky bluff on the north side of the channel has 3 sites I will want to attend to next breeding season. 2 are at the extreme ends of the cliff and those look suitable for Turkey Vultures. One in the middle is a regular raven or Red-tail stick nest that was active this breeding season, but inactive now. A nest on 'Chalk Cliff' was mentioned in Duval's 1994 and 1995 notes that are scanned and held in the Park Naturalists' office and at CCBER at UCSB. Bird list is formed mostly from just 3 stops along my route shown in red on an aerial photo dated 3 February 2018. ----Photo was taken from my west-most stop on the route in red.----Chalk Bluff
SPECIES COMMENTS: Adult sitting on a snag in the lake just north of Arrowhead Island.

TRIP COMMENTS: The trip was a Western Field Ornithologists charter on the Island Explorer with Island Packers for a combined pelagic trip and Santa Cruz Island landing to look for the Island Scrub-Jay. On this leg we disembarked at Prisoners Harbor and split up into several groups to look for the Island Scrub-Jay and migrants on the island. Not all birds were seen by everyone due to the split parties. A dead Greater White-fronted Goose found at the creek mouth was likely one of the two that were seen there on 27 Sep 2018. Weather was sunny and warm with light winds. Leaders were David Pereksta, Peter Gaede, Scott Terrill, and Kurt Leuschner.----

TRIP COMMENTS: With Vicki Silvas-Young; covered the area around the active landfill for the Calero-Morgan Hill Christmas Bird Count. Gull numbers much lower than in prior years. First gulls arrived about 0720. Only Herring and Thayer's Gulls (and one flyby Mew) were present until 0800 when the first Glaucous-winged arrived. The first California Gull showed up at 0817. The last gulls were on the ground at 1055, though some continued to fly around overhead until around 1230.

SPECIES COMMENTS: So exciting to see a Bald Eagle from our driveway - new yard bird! Our attention was grabbed by the Osprey flying directly overhead calling loudly, while the Eagle was in hot pursuit. They circled overhead. The Osprey then dropped prey from its talons, and the Eagle swooped it up mid air. The Osprey then proceeded to chase the Eagle. They circled once more overhead, before both flying out of sight towards the river. They were so low overhead we watched the drama unfold even though we didn't have binoculars on hand. It was amazing!

Observers: Harold and Sherrie Reeve. This checklist was made as a part of our February run of the Oakdale route of our Winter Raptor Survey. Our emphasis was on surveying all raptors found within 500 m of the road, but we did note other birds and recorded all species that we were able to identify. This Winter Raptor Survey route begins at the canal crossing near the south end of Crabtree Rd. and runs nearly 32 miles along Crabtree, Warnerville, and Willms roads, through Knights Ferry, west on Sonora Rd., north on 28 Rd. past Woodward Reservoir, and ending at the intersection of 28 Mile Rd. and Dorsey Rd. Today's weather conditions good visibility with clear to partly cloudy skies, temperatures between 54 and 62 degrees F, and westerly winds beginning and ending at Beaufort 4, diminishing to Beaufort 3 for much of the morning and rising to Beaufort 5 during the mid to late afternoon.

LOCALITY: Tuolumne River--Basso Bridge to Turlock Lake SRA campground
TRIP COMMENTS: Birding while paddling the river by kayak from Basso Bridge fishing access to the campground at Turlock Lake SRA. The river was quite high at 854 csf. The river was quite birdy for most of the way, but we were paddling into a wind that was brisk enough to make hearing birds difficult at times and less than optimum most of the time. At approximately the halfway point, just downstream of the largest earthen cliffs where the river branches out around two islands, we took a small fork toward the north and followed a canal-like river channel for nearly 0.6 mile until the water branched in several directions, including two dammed by small beaver dams and several that filtered their ways through trees and brush. We considered bypassing one end of the largest beaver dam, but did not know what lay ahead, so we took the prudent course of action and scouted a portage route about 150 m long south to the main river. We saw no birds along the portage route. Weather: partly cloudy, 75-70 degrees F, wind WNW at 10-15 mph.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Both were in trees along the first narrow area with riffles downstream from Basso Bridge, perhaps 50 m apart from each other.

LOCALITY: Crabtree Rd.--Dry Creek bridge to Warnerville Rd.
TRIP COMMENTS: Birding during a part of our 32-mile Oakdale Winter Raptor Survey route. Our emphasis was, of course, on roadside raptors (within 500 m on either side of the road), and we are reporting here other species we saw along the way and raptors seen beyond 500 m from the road. Conditions were excellent but the road shoulders were often soft or muddy, limiting our ability to pull off the road and scan for or verify the identity of birds in some places. Weather throughout the day included: clear skies early becoming partly cloudy with cumulous by mid day and cirrus and high stratus moving in from the west during the mid and late afternoon; temperature beginning at 46 degrees F and ending at 50 F, with a high of about 55 degrees; winds calm early, increasing to 5-7 mph W in early afternoon, and calming to W at 2-3 mph by sunset.
SPECIES COMMENTS: One adult and one immature Bal Eagle were sitting at the top of a tree about 0.5 mile east of Crabtree Rd. beyond the large grain field where the road turns north and away from Dry Creek. These were the only Bald Eagles we saw today and because they were beyond 500 m from the road the species went unrecorded on our roadside survey.

LOCALITY: Pt. Mugu Naval Air Station (restricted access)
TRIP COMMENTS: Birds recorded during Thousand Oaks CBC. Surveyed nearly entire base including Mugu Lagoon (mouth and causeway), marshes in restricted area, perimeter road along edges of hunt clubs, residential neighborhoods and adjacent areas, ballfields, old golf course, airfields, and beaches. Waterfowl numbers were lower than expected with some species nearly absent in the lagoon. Gull diversity was also low.----Conditions were fair and cool, with temps starting at 41F and peaking at 60F. Skies were generally clear with more clouds building in the afternoon (60%). Winds were mild at 5 to 10 mph from the NE. Seas were calm for seawatching in the morning, but early heat shimmer was problematic for viewing. We repeatedly covered several areas and did cover the majority of the installation's 4,500 acres.----All birding for this list was by one party; David Pereksta, Martin Ruane, Giles Pettifor, and Justina Martelli. They were joined in the early-morning by Andrew Partin who soon split off to cover areas in the neighborhoods and around the airfield. His list is entered separately.

LOCALITY: Yolo Bypass Wildlife Area--Auto Tour Route
TRIP COMMENTS: At 7 a.m. I met Sonia Santa Anna at the Starbuck's on Mace. We drove to the Yolo Bypass Wildlife Area and birded the Auto tour route. Unlike my recent visit with Cheryl Cobbs, today there was a little high fog early on but I was able to use my scope whenever looking at distant birds. Unfortunately, Sonia had to send her scope in for repair so she did not have one today.  Turns out that worked extremely well for us since she spotted all kinds of birds while scanning with her binocular when I was scanning distant birds with my scope.  One of her many finds today was the immature Bald Eagle that had ducks flying in all directions.----I was bummed that I again missed the Swamp Sparrow everybody else seems to see.  When we returned for another look around noon, the water level in the canal was more than a foot higher as water poured in from a source near the levee.----It was a terrific morning and now at 11:30 p.m. I am too tired to try to list all the great birds spotted by Sonia.  Suffice it to say she was superb!

TRIP COMMENTS: Have been wanting to try another, more direct route up to the ridge. I jogged up the trail for about 1.5 until the ridgeline outcropping looks to be directly above you. At this point there is a game trail directly upslope, which I took. This takes you to the base of the cliff, then traverses beneath it to the right. This path appears to be used often by deer, as told by the tracks, droppings and antler remnants. After passing on a few treacherous gullys up, I chose one, which looked to be the deers' favorite, and scrambled up to the ridgeline. This was just 70 meters or so south of the initial rock cornice seen from the road/trailhead. From here it was dense chaparral with no clear trail up the ridgeline, unfortunately, so I turned around. Perhaps a different gully ties into the ridgeline trail. This route is 1.8 miles one-way instead of the 3.3 to the ridge via the trail. 40 min bird-joggin up, 10 min at the top, 25 down. Plus some parking lot birding.
